{{BLP sources|date=October 2013}} '''Michael D. Swords''' is a retired professor of [[Natural Science]] at [[Western Michigan University]], who writes about general sciences and anomalous phenomena, particularly [[parapsychology]], [[cryptozoology]], and [[ufology]], editing the academic publication ''The Journal of UFO Studies''. He is a board member of the [[J. Allen Hynek Center for UFO Studies]].
==Biography==
In 1962 Swords graduated from the [[University of Notre Dame]] with a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]]. He studied [[biochemistry]] at [[Iowa State University]] (where he earned his [[Master of Science|M.S.]]), and at [[Case Western Reserve University]] (where he earned his [[Ph.D.]] in 1972).
Swords recently{{vague|date=December 2013}} retired as a [[professor]] of [[natural sciences]] at [[Western Michigan University]], where he received a Teaching Excellence award in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manitouarbor.org/who-we-are |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-10-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217225531/http://www.manitouarbor.org/who-we-are |archivedate=2013-12-17 |df= }}</ref>
As a ufologist, Swords is an authority on the [[Condon Committee]]. He was editor of the ''Journal for UFO Studies''.<ref>http://sohp.us/sign_oral_history_project/usaf/annotated_bibliography.php</ref> He was a prominently featured [[Pundit (expert)|pundit]] on the prime time 2005 television special ''[[Peter Jennings]] Reporting: UFOs — Seeing Is Believing'', discussing the early history of the U.S. Military's UFO investigations (see also [[Project Sign]] and [[Project Grudge]].)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Ts8DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA64 ''Popular Mechanics''], May 2001</ref>
