The '''Spartia temple''' is an [[ancient Greece|ancient Greek]] [[Greek temple|temple]] and [[archaeological site]] on the hill of [[Spartia]], [[Sesklo]], in the [[Magnesia (regional unit)|Magnesia regional unit]]. The temple is thought to be dedicated to the [[Greek mythology|Greek mythological figures]] [[Heracles]] and [[Alcmene]].
[[Archaeologists]] have discovered many [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]] on the site of the [[sanctuary]], which is thought to date to the [[Archaic period in Greece|archaic period]]. Items recovered include [[bronze]] [[vase]]s, objects of [[lead]] and [[clay]], [[weapon]]s, [[iron]] [[tool]]s, and [[figurine]]s. Some specific artifacts named are clay [[Metope (architecture)|metopes]] with yellow [[wiktionary:veneer|veneer]], [[spear]]heads, and part of the arm of a [[Marble sculpture|marble]] [[Ancient Greek sculpture|statue]].
One important artifact is a bronze flask (described as "navel-shaped") in excellent condition with the inscription "Tilephilos dedicated me to Herakles" in the [[History of the Greek alphabet|archaic Greek alphabet]]. This indicates the presence of a Herakles [[Cult (religious practice)|cult]], which is linked to [[Pherae]] and is documented in the region through [[Hellenistic civilization|Hellenistic-era]] inscriptions.
The flask had been found several years before its value was recognized when a [[natural gas]] [[Pipeline transport|pipeline]] was built near the hill of Spartia by the Volos-Velestinos-Larissa highway (on the site of the ancient Pherae-Pagasses road). Put in storage by the XII Ephorate of Prehistoric and Classical Antiquities of the [[Minister for Culture (Greece)|Ministry for Culture]], the object was rediscovered when it was cleaned during conservation work.
